				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sunnyclockwork" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1621343); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1621343&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250340" alt="SunnyClockwork" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1621343)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sunnyclockwork" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1621343); return false;" >SunnyClockwork</a></span> <span class="odate time_1451406716 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">29 Dec 2015 16:31</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2430547">
									

<p>A tale of a gurad in the City of <a href="/scp-2264">Alagadda</a>. Huge thanks to those who took a look at it :3</p>
<p>Art by me, but special thanks to 守辰 for helping me with the gif.</p>
<p>Ties in a little with some of my other Alagadda/Hanged King tales, especially <a href="/and-so-the-crows-laughed">And so the Crows Laughed</a> and <a href="/of-dragons-and-serpents">Of Dragons and Serpents</a>. But I think it won't be too much of a problem if you didn't read them :3 If things goes as plan, I will be posting another tale as a follow-up to this, and a sequel to And so the Crows Laughed soon.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Spoilers</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Spoilers</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>The tales aims to illustrate what happens in Alagadda from an individual's point of view, or what its normal citizens had been through. In this case its a gate guard, who, after the city became what it is now, become disassociated with his actual past. And here in Alagadda, he is and will always be the guard.</p>
<p>The clock isn't actually representing the passage of time, but a countdown. As the number goes from twelve to eventually zero, the city spirals down into, or reveals more and more of its madness. The change of tenses bewteen different sections however, does represent the chaotic flow of time in the city.</p>
<p>The non-italicized text are actual events in Alagadda, or in some cases, the events yet to come. The italizcized text are the guard trying to recall what had happened before the city become what it is. This part is mainly a short retelling of <a href="/and-so-the-crows-laughed">And so the Crows Laughed</a> from the guard's view, except for the Dragon's part. The Dragon, and it's Absence/The God Shaped Hole, is explained in <a href="/of-dragons-and-serpents">Of Dragons and Serpents</a>'s fifth's poem to be Yadabaoth/The Sarkic God, with whom the Hanged King pacted with.</p>
<p>&quot;A parade will be coming as people step on the body of their former Lord. &quot; refers to the event in my tale <a href="/midnight-parade">Midnight Parade</a>, where the Black Lord is casted out of the Court.</p>
<p>A lost traveler could be refering to the Wandsman in <a href="/a-wandsman-in-the-court-of-the-hanged-king">A Wandsman in the Court of the Hanged King</a>, but could also be others, like the writer of the dragon peom.</p>
<p>The end of the tale predicts the end of the Alagadda, where the Dragon, who has received enough offering from the city, broke free of its cage and destoryed the city and its inhabitants. The Guard is an unfortunately soul who happened to stumble upon the dragon/its absence, and is bound by the duty to guard the place.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

