														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2430668">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;This&nbsp;could&nbsp;have&nbsp;used&nbsp;a&nbsp;proofreading.</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;hide&nbsp;text</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>The clock stroke twelve</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The clock <em>struck</em> twelve.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>their faces covered by masks of masquerade</p>
</blockquote>
<p>&quot;Masks of masquerade&quot; isn't a mistake, per se, but it is way too repetitive.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The guard will be standing there as the mob drag the twisted body</p>
</blockquote>
<p>as the mob <em>drags</em>.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>he is standing there as they tells him to come to the castle</p>
</blockquote>
<p>as they <em>tell</em> him</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The dead has been walking and parading all this time</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The dead <em>have</em> been walking</p>
<hr /></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In addition to the errors above, this is all over the place in terms of tenses. The writing goes back and forth between present and past tense, sometimes within the same paragraph, for no apparent reason. Maybe it has something to do with the fluidity of time within whatever this place is, but the end result doesn't really capture that quality; it's merely confusing.</p>
<p>More so than those issues, though, there's a very flashlight-under-the-chin quality to this. This isn't really a narrative, as such. This is supposedly centered on a palace guard and his perspective, but there's no character there, no perspective outside of whatever the reader chooses to bring to the tale. The only thing I know about what is supposedly the central character here is that he sees a lot of scary stuff.</p>
<p>This isn't a story, as much as it's just a collection of images that I've seen before in superior pieces. Those pieces, incidentally, were superior because they were more than just a presentation of spooky imagery. The imagery in those cases served a purpose there other than just existing. If there is a larger purpose, as I take the lengthy &quot;spoiler&quot; section above to suggest, it has little to do with what's actually written here.</p>

							</div>

								
