			<div class="content" id="post-content-2430999">
									

<p>Now that, my friend, is <em>writing</em>.<br />
It is extremely difficult to successfully give priority to writing over story/characters, but I think you've done it well here.<br />
I disagree with Kalinin - except re: the typos, which have been corrected in the meantime. <em>Of course</em> the tense changes are confusing; this is, IMO, a deliberate <em>effect</em>. The scene is confusing - or perhaps I should say <em>the events are confusing</em>; the narrator is confused; so the reader should be confused. Nothing wrong with that if it's well done, and I do think it is.<br />
I don't know the context yet, and I enjoyed the tale anyway. Gonna have myself some reading, and come back to this afterwards; shall keep you posted on whether it consequently deserves +5, or if I'll stick to my single upvote! &lt;grin&gt;</p>
<p>Oh, just a thought: me, I would have mixed up tenses, more and more as we come closer to the end of reality, past/present/future etc. (even combinations like, for instance, <em>will guarded</em>) all jumbled including within sentences, to render the chaos even more. What do you think?</p>

							</div>

								
					
